//familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:J6HD-Y62|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Popule|first=|date=1920|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMarie was the niece of Marie Populova.\n|\n|-\n|4 May 1947\n[[RMS Queen Elizabeth]]\n\n[[Southampton]][[File:RMS Queen Elizabeth Southampton.jpg|center|thumb|At port in Southampton]]<br />\n|9 May 1947\n[[New York City|New York]]\n|[https://www.familysearch.org/tree/person/details/L124-G5X Moutvic - Barbora (1893-)]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:24PN-FMB|title=New York, New York Passenger and Crew Lists, 1909, 1925-1957|last=Moutvic|first=|date=1947|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nShe had a family in [[Prague]] and was probably only visiting her brother Karel.\n|\n|-\n|\n|before 1952\n|[https://www.familysearch.org/tree/person/G9P4-X2K Mares - Frantisek (1920-2001)]\n\nFrantisek was the nephew of Marie and Filomena Maresova.\n|\n|}\n\n== Population ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Population\n|-\n|1880\n|344<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426168|title=Census 1880 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo), Nr. 47 {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|1890\n|293<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426169/soap-kt_01159_census-sum-1890-nehodiv_0030?x=-40&y=268&w=541&h=239|title=Census 1890 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo) - souhrn / Sammelbogen {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1900\n|306<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426219/soap-kt_01159_census-sum-1900-nehodiv_0160?x=260&y=69&w=680&h=301|title=Census 1900 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo) - souhrn / Sammelbogen {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1910\n|291<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426270/soap-kt_01159_census-sum-1910-nehodiv_0020?x=229&y=-2&w=813&h=360|title=Census 1910 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo) - souhrn / Sammelbogen {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1921\n|262<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426372?x=-57&y=437&w=1092&h=581|title=Census 1921 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo), Nr. 52 {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|28&nbsp;August 2006\n|79\n|}\n\n== Facts ==\nThere is a chapel with a computer-controlled bell in the center of the village. There is also a limestone quarry from which white limestone is extracted. The village is towered by St\u00edrka Hill, which dominates the general area with its height of 702 m above sea level. Southwest of the village is a natural monument Dolejsi drahy .\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Nehodiv, zat\u00e1\u010dka.jpg|Houses\nFile:Nehodiv6.jpg|House\nFile:Nehodiv5.jpg|Village square with tree\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080618131004/http://www.czso.cz/lexikon/mos_vdb.nsf/okresy/CZ0322/ Czech Statistical Office: Municipalities of Klatovy District]\n\n{{commons category|Nehodiv}}\n{{Klatovy District}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Klatovy District]]\n", "name_user": "Jonnychiwa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGenealogy and Immigration to America", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nehodiv"}
{"title_page": "Backpacking (travel)", "text_new": "{{About|backpacking while travelling||Backpacking (disambiguation){{!}}Backpacking}}\n<!-- PLEASE READ: This page does not concern details of individual trips. WRITE OBJECTIVELY!]] -->\n[[File:Urban backpacking.jpg|thumb|Backpackers in front of the [[Vienna State Opera]] in July 2005]]\n\n'''Backpacking''' is a form of low-cost, independent travel, often staying in inexpensive lodgings and carrying all necesary possessions in a [[backpack]]. Once seen as a marginal form of travel undertaken only through necessity, it has since become a mainstream form of tourism.<ref>{{cite journal | title=From Drifter to Gap Year Tourist Mainstreaming Backpacker Travel | journal=Annals of Tourism Research | year=2006 | first=Camille | last=Caprioglio O'Reilly | volume=33 | issue=4 | pages=998\u20131017 | doi=10.1016/j.annals.2006.04.002 }}</ref>\n\nWhile backpacker tourism is generally a form of [[youth travel]], primarily undertaken by young people during [[gap year]]s, it is also undertaken by older people during a career break or retirement. Backpackers tend to be from [[Europe]], the [[English-speaking world]] and [[Asia]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidyin/2013/12/19/out-of-israel-into-the-world/ | title=Out Of Israel, Into The World | first=David | last=Yin | work=[[Forbes]] | date=December 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nBackpacker tourism generally, but does not always, include:<ref>{{cite web | url=https://sk.sagepub.com/reference/the-sage-international-encyclopedia-of-travel-and-tourism/i2343.xml | title=Backpacker Tourism | first=Catherine | last=Kelly | via=[[SAGE Publishing]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/249023759 | title=Backpacker tourism: sustainable and purposeful? Investigating the overlap between backpacker tourism and volunteer tourism motivations | first1=Natalie | last1=Ooi | first2=Jennifer H. | last2=Laing | publisher=[[Journal of Sustainable Tourism]] | via=[[ResearchGate]] | date=March 2010}}</ref>\n* Traveling mostly via [[public transport]].\n* Using inexpensive lodging such as [[hostel]]s or [[homestay]]s.\n* A longer duration trip when compared with conventional vacations.\n* An interest in meeting locals as well as seeing sights.\n* An interest in meeting other travelers.\n* Use of [[smartphone]]s and online resources for planning.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Backpackers' experiences with smartphones usage in Ghana | journal=Anatolia | volume=30 | issue=3 | pages=390\u2013403 | first=Frederick | last=Dayour | date=27 March 2019| doi=10.1080/13032917.2019.1597741 }}</ref>\n* Carrying belongings in a [[backpack]]. Backpackers have traditionally carried their possessions in 30 liter to 60 liter backpacks, but roller-wheeled suitcases and some less-traditional carrying methods have become more common, and there has been a trend towards keeping pack weights under the 8-to-10 kilogram carry-on limit of most airlines.<ref>\n{{cite news | first=Susan | last=Catto | title=PRACTICAL TRAVELER; The 'Pack' Of Backpacking | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/14/travel/practical-traveler-the-pack-of-backpacking.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 14, 2002 | url-access=subscription | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n* Backpacker tourism may also include working in various countries for short stints, depending on [[work permit]] laws.<ref name=BTAP>{{cite web | last=Victoria | first=Government | title=Backpacker Tourism Action Plan | url=https://www.business.vic.gov.au/tourism-industry-resources | publisher=Tourism Victoria}}</ref> It can also be undertaken by [[digital nomad]]s, people who work using technology while living a nomadic lifestyle.\n* A sense of [[authenticity (philosophy)|authenticity]]. Backpacking is perceived not only as a form of [[tourism]], but a means of education.<ref>{{cite journal | title=A \"University of Travel\": Backpacker Learning | journal=Tourism Management | year=2007 | first1=Philip | last1=Pearce | first2=Faith | last2=Foster | volume=28 | issue=5 | pages=1285\u20131298 | doi=10.1016/j.tourman.2006.11.009}}\n</ref> Backpackers want to experience what they consider the \"real\" destination rather than a packaged version often associated with mass tourism.<ref>{{cite book | last1=Richards | first1=Greg | first2=Julie | last2=Wilson | title=The Global Nomad: Backpacker Theory in Travel and Practice | publisher=[[Channel View Publications]] | pages=80\u201391 | url =https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Global_Nomad.html?id=S8qBAAAAMAAJ | isbn=1-873150-76-8 | date=March 29, 2004}}\n</ref>\n\n==History==\nPeople have travelled for thousands of years with their possessions on their backs, but usually out of need rather than for recreation.\n\nIn the 17th century, Italian adventurer [[Giovanni Francesco Gemelli Careri]] was likely one of the first people to engage in backpacker tourism.<ref>{{cite news | title=The Inventor of Traveling - The First Backpacker in the World? | date=July 2007 | url=http://www.infohostels.com/notizia.php?chiave=200 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212000017/http://www.infohostels.com/notizia.php?chiave=200 | archivedate=12 December 2007 | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n\nThe modern popularity of backpacking can be traced, at least partially, to the [[hippie trail]] of the 1960s and 1970s,<ref name=Diversity>{{cite journal | title=Backpacking: Diversity and Change | journal=Tourism and Cultural Change | year=2003 | first=Erik | last=Cohen | volume=1 | issue=2 | pages=95\u2013110 | doi=10.1080/14766820308668162}}</ref> which in turn followed sections of the old [[Silk Road]]. Some backpackers follow the same trail today.<ref>\n{{cite news | first=Jennifer | last=Conlin | title=IN TRANSIT; Traveling to the Ends of the Earth, at Ground Level | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/11/travel/11transbus.html?sec=travel | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 11, 2007 | url-access=subscription | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n\nSince the late-20th century, backpackers have visited [[Southeast Asia]] in large numbers<ref>{{cite web | title=Travel & Tourism Economic Impact 2018 South East Asia | url=https://www.wttc.org/-/media/files/reports/economic-impact-research/regions-2018/southeastasia2018.pdf | website=World Travel & Tourism Council | publisher=World Travel & Tourism Council}}</ref>\n\n===Benefits===\nA 2018 study of over 500 backpackers conducted by researchers at [[Sun Yat-sen University]] and [[Shaanxi Normal University]] in China and [[Edith Cowan University]] in Australia showed that for Westerners, backpacking leads to acquired capabilities like effective communication, [[decision-making]], [[adaptability]], and [[problem solving]], all of which contribute to an increase in [[self-efficacy]], and for Chinese backpackers, acquiring skills like time and [[money management]], language development, [[stress management]], and self-motivation provided the biggest increase in self-efficacy.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/travel-news/backpacking-better-more-successful-person | title=How a Backpacking Trip Could Make You a More Successful Person | first=TALIA | last=AVAKIAN | work=[[Travel + Leisure]] | date=August 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title=Backpacker Personal Development, Generalized Self-Efficacy, and Self-Esteem: Testing a Structural Model | first1=Ganghua | last1=Chen | first2=Songshan (Sam) | last2=Huang | first3=Xianyang | last3=Hu | journal=[[Journal of Travel Research]] | volume=58 | issue=4 | pages=680\u2013694 | date=May 3, 2018| doi=10.1177/0047287518768457 }}</ref>\n\nFor many low-income communities in the developing world, the economic benefits of hosting backpackers outweigh their negative impacts. Since backpackers tend to consume local products, stay in small guest houses, and use locally owned ground transport, more of their expenditure is retained in-country than in conventional mass tourism. businesses that cater to backpackers are usually locally owned and profits tend to be retained within the country rather than flowing overseas to international hotel groups.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/sep/24/backpacker-travel-benefit-poor-countries | title=Backpacker tourism can be beneficial for poor countries | first=Mark | last=Hampton | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=September 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\nBackpacker tourism of the [[hippie trail]] has been criticized for possibly encouraging urban liberal minorities while insulting [[Traditionalist theology (Islam)|Islamic traditionalist theology]], possibly leading to the Islamic reawakening in the late 1970s.<ref>{{cite news | first=Rory | last=MacLean | title=Dark Side of the Hippie Trail | url=https://www.newstatesman.com/node/164904 | work=[[The New Statesman]] | date=July 31, 2006 | url-status= live}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KmlYvgEACAAJ | title=Magic Bus: On the Hippie Trail from Istanbul to India | first=Rory | last=MacLean | publisher=[[Ig Publishing]] | date=2009| isbn=9780978843199 }}</ref>\n\nEven though one of the primary aims of backpacking is to seek the \"authentic\", the majority of backpackers spend most of their time interacting with other backpackers, and interactions with locals are of \"secondary importance\".<ref name=Diversity/>\n\nBackpacker tourism has been criticized for the transformation of some sleepy towns, such as the creation of the [[Full Moon Party]] on [[Ko Pha-ngan]] in [[Thailand]], which includes \"scores of topless teenagers urinating into the ocean\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2010/sep/06/gap-year-thailand-full-moon-party | title=Gap years: Wasted youth? | first=Patrick | last=Kingsley | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=September 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n'''Flashpacking''' and '''Poshpacking''' refer to backpacking with more money and resources. The words combine ''backpacking'' with ''flash'', a slang term for being fancy, or ''posh'', an informal adjective for [[upper class]].<ref>{{cite news | first=Ben | last=Groundwater | title=Are you a backpacker, or a poshpacker? | url=http://blogs.smh.com.au/travel/archives/2007/01/are_you_a_backpacker_or_a_posh.html | work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | date=January 16, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title='Flashpacking?' Don't Forget you Still Need Room for Extra Socks | url=https://www.usatoday.com/travel/destinations/2006-06-19-flashpacking_x.htm | agency=[[Associated Press]] | publisher=[[USA Today]] | date=June 20, 2006}}</ref>\n\n'''Begpacking''' combines ''begging'' and ''backpacking'' in reference to individuals who [[Begging|beg]] (ask directly or indirectly for money), solicit money during [[street performance]]s, or vend (sell postcards or other small items) as a way to extend their overseas travel.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Bernstein | first=J.D. | year=2019 | title=Begging to travel: Begpacking in Southeast Asia. | journal=Annals of Tourism Research | volume=77 | pages=77, 161\u2013163 | doi=10.1016/j.annals.2018.12.014 }}</ref> The trend has drawn criticism for taking money away from people in actual need, with one known begpacker barred from entering [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Notorious begpacker barred from entering S'pore, goes around the world begging | date=April 13, 2017 | url=https://mothership.sg/2017/04/notorious-begpacker-barred-from-entering-spore/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/329837273 | title=Begging to travel: Begpacking in Southeast Asia | first=Joshua D. | last=Bernstein | date=December 2018}}</ref> Begpacking is most common in Southeast Asia and is a growing trend in South America.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/shortcuts/2019/jul/22/young-entitled-and-over-there-the-rise-of-the-begpacker | title=Young, entitled, and over there: The rise of the begpacker | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=July 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://medium.com/@MajSB/begpackers-seen-by-a-third-worldist-585d408db401 | title=Begpackers seen by a third-worldist | first=Majda | last=Saidi | work=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] | date=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary-inline|backpacking}}\n<!-- PLEASE READ: Commercial links not expanding on the article do NOT belong here.. [[Wikipedia:External links]] -->\n\n<!-- EXTERNAL LINKS SHOULD FILL THE FOLLOWING CRITERIA:\n* Be based wholly about the domain of backpacking (independent travel) and not other forms of travel,\n* Be non-Commercial with no external, banner/other ads or be linked to a commercial organisation in anyway,\n* Be recognised as expanding on the article and field of the article\n* Be maintained and up-to date.\n* BLOGS, TRAVEL-LOGS, TRIP BASE SITES - and similar do not belong here, nor does anything commercial such as Lonely Planet et al.\n[[Wikipedia:External links]] -->\n\n{{Wikivoyage-inline|Urban backpacking}}\n\n{{Tourism}}\n{{Adventure travel}}\n{{Orienteering}}\n\n<!-- REMEMBER: Commercial links not expanding on the article do NOT belong here.. [[Wikipedia:External links]] -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Backpacker tourism}}\n[[Category:Backpacking|*]]\n[[Category:Youth hostelling]]\n[[Category:Hitchhiking]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|backpacking while travelling||Backpacking (disambiguation){{!}}Backpacking}}\n<!-- PLEASE READ: This page does not concern details of individual trips. WRITE OBJECTIVELY!]] -->\n[[File:Urban backpacking.jpg|thumb|Backpackers in front of the [[Vienna State Opera]] in July 2005]]\n\n'''Backpacking''' is a form of low-cost, independent travel, often staying in inexpensive lodging and carrying all necesary possessions in a [[backpack]]. Once seen as a marginal form of travel undertaken only through necessity, it has since become a mainstream form of tourism.<ref>{{cite journal | title=From Drifter to Gap Year Tourist Mainstreaming Backpacker Travel | journal=Annals of Tourism Research | year=2006 | first=Camille | last=Caprioglio O'Reilly | volume=33 | issue=4 | pages=998\u20131017 | doi=10.1016/j.annals.2006.04.002 }}</ref>\n\nWhile backpacker tourism is generally a form of [[youth travel]], primarily undertaken by young people during [[gap year]]s, it is also undertaken by older people during a career break or retirement. Backpackers tend to be from [[Europe]], the [[English-speaking world]], [[Asia]], or [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidyin/2013/12/19/out-of-israel-into-the-world/ | title=Out Of Israel, Into The World | first=David | last=Yin | work=[[Forbes]] | date=December 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nBackpacker tourism generally, but does not always, include:<ref>{{cite web | url=https://sk.sagepub.com/reference/the-sage-international-encyclopedia-of-travel-and-tourism/i2343.xml | title=Backpacker Tourism | first=Catherine | last=Kelly | via=[[SAGE Publishing]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/249023759 | title=Backpacker tourism: sustainable and purposeful? Investigating the overlap between backpacker tourism and volunteer tourism motivations | first1=Natalie | last1=Ooi | first2=Jennifer H. | last2=Laing | publisher=[[Journal of Sustainable Tourism]] | via=[[ResearchGate]] | date=March 2010}}</ref>\n* Traveling mostly via [[public transport]].\n* Using inexpensive lodging such as [[hostel]]s or [[homestay]]s.\n* A longer duration trip when compared with conventional vacations.\n* An interest in meeting locals as well as seeing sights.\n* An interest in meeting other travelers.\n* Use of [[smartphone]]s and online resources for planning.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Backpackers' experiences with smartphones usage in Ghana | journal=Anatolia | volume=30 | issue=3 | pages=390\u2013403 | first=Frederick | last=Dayour | date=27 March 2019| doi=10.1080/13032917.2019.1597741 }}</ref>\n* Carrying belongings in a [[backpack]]. Backpackers have traditionally carried their possessions in 30 liter to 60 liter backpacks, but roller-wheeled suitcases and some less-traditional carrying methods have become more common, and there has been a trend towards keeping pack weights under the 8-to-10 kilogram carry-on limit of most airlines.<ref>\n{{cite news | first=Susan | last=Catto | title=PRACTICAL TRAVELER; The 'Pack' Of Backpacking | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/14/travel/practical-traveler-the-pack-of-backpacking.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 14, 2002 | url-access=subscription | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n* Backpacker tourism may also include working in various countries for short stints, depending on [[work permit]] laws.<ref name=BTAP>{{cite web | last=Victoria | first=Government | title=Backpacker Tourism Action Plan | url=https://www.business.vic.gov.au/tourism-industry-resources | publisher=Tourism Victoria}}</ref> It can also be undertaken by [[digital nomad]]s, people who work using technology while living a nomadic lifestyle.\n* A sense of [[authenticity (philosophy)|authenticity]]. Backpacking is perceived not only as a form of [[tourism]], but a means of education.<ref>{{cite journal | title=A \"University of Travel\": Backpacker Learning | journal=Tourism Management | year=2007 | first1=Philip | last1=Pearce | first2=Faith | last2=Foster | volume=28 | issue=5 | pages=1285\u20131298 | doi=10.1016/j.tourman.2006.11.009}}\n</ref> Backpackers want to experience what they consider the \"real\" destination rather than a packaged version often associated with mass tourism.<ref>{{cite book | last1=Richards | first1=Greg | first2=Julie | last2=Wilson | title=The Global Nomad: Backpacker Theory in Travel and Practice | publisher=[[Channel View Publications]] | pages=80\u201391 | url =https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Global_Nomad.html?id=S8qBAAAAMAAJ | isbn=1-873150-76-8 | date=March 29, 2004}}\n</ref>\n\n==History==\nPeople have travelled for thousands of years with their possessions on their backs, but usually out of need rather than for recreation.\n\nIn the 17th century, Italian adventurer [[Giovanni Francesco Gemelli Careri]] was likely one of the first people to engage in backpacker tourism.<ref>{{cite news | title=The Inventor of Traveling - The First Backpacker in the World? | date=July 2007 | url=http://www.infohostels.com/notizia.php?chiave=200 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212000017/http://www.infohostels.com/notizia.php?chiave=200 | archivedate=12 December 2007 | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n\nThe modern popularity of backpacking can be traced, at least partially, to the [[hippie trail]] of the 1960s and 1970s,<ref name=Diversity>{{cite journal | title=Backpacking: Diversity and Change | journal=Tourism and Cultural Change | year=2003 | first=Erik | last=Cohen | volume=1 | issue=2 | pages=95\u2013110 | doi=10.1080/14766820308668162}}</ref> which in turn followed sections of the old [[Silk Road]]. Some backpackers follow the same trail today.<ref>\n{{cite news | first=Jennifer | last=Conlin | title=IN TRANSIT; Traveling to the Ends of the Earth, at Ground Level | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/11/travel/11transbus.html?sec=travel | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 11, 2007 | url-access=subscription | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n\nSince the late-20th century, backpackers have visited [[Southeast Asia]] in large numbers<ref>{{cite web | title=Travel & Tourism Economic Impact 2018 South East Asia | url=https://www.wttc.org/-/media/files/reports/economic-impact-research/regions-2018/southeastasia2018.pdf | website=World Travel & Tourism Council | publisher=World Travel & Tourism Council}}</ref>\n\n===Benefits===\nA 2018 study of over 500 backpackers conducted by researchers at [[Sun Yat-sen University]] and [[Shaanxi Normal University]] in China and [[Edith Cowan University]] in Australia showed that for Westerners, backpacking leads to acquired capabilities like effective communication, [[decision-making]], [[adaptability]], and [[problem solving]], all of which contribute to an increase in [[self-efficacy]], and for Chinese backpackers, acquiring skills like time and [[money management]], language development, [[stress management]], and self-motivation provided the biggest increase in self-efficacy.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/travel-news/backpacking-better-more-successful-person | title=How a Backpacking Trip Could Make You a More Successful Person | first=TALIA | last=AVAKIAN | work=[[Travel + Leisure]] | date=August 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title=Backpacker Personal Development, Generalized Self-Efficacy, and Self-Esteem: Testing a Structural Model | first1=Ganghua | last1=Chen | first2=Songshan (Sam) | last2=Huang | first3=Xianyang | last3=Hu | journal=[[Journal of Travel Research]] | volume=58 | issue=4 | pages=680\u2013694 | date=May 3, 2018| doi=10.1177/0047287518768457 }}</ref>\n\nFor many low-income communities in the developing world, the economic benefits of hosting backpackers outweigh their negative impacts. Since backpackers tend to consume local products, stay in small guest houses, and use locally owned ground transport, more of their expenditure is retained in-country than in conventional mass tourism. businesses that cater to backpackers are usually locally owned and profits tend to be retained within the country rather than flowing overseas to international hotel groups.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/sep/24/backpacker-travel-benefit-poor-countries | title=Backpacker tourism can be beneficial for poor countries | first=Mark | last=Hampton | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=September 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\nBackpacker tourism of the [[hippie trail]] has been criticized for possibly encouraging urban liberal minorities while insulting [[Traditionalist theology (Islam)|Islamic traditionalist theology]], possibly leading to the Islamic reawakening in the late 1970s.<ref>{{cite news | first=Rory | last=MacLean | title=Dark Side of the Hippie Trail | url=https://www.newstatesman.com/node/164904 | work=[[The New Statesman]] | date=July 31, 2006 | url-status= live}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KmlYvgEACAAJ | title=Magic Bus: On the Hippie Trail from Istanbul to India | first=Rory | last=MacLean | publisher=[[Ig Publishing]] | date=2009| isbn=9780978843199 }}</ref>\n\nEven though one of the primary aims of backpacking is to seek the \"authentic\", the majority of backpackers spend most of their time interacting with other backpackers, and interactions with locals are of \"secondary importance\".<ref name=Diversity/>\n\nBackpacker tourism has been criticized for the transformation of some sleepy towns, such as the creation of the [[Full Moon Party]] on [[Ko Pha-ngan]] in [[Thailand]], which includes \"scores of topless teenagers urinating into the ocean\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2010/sep/06/gap-year-thailand-full-moon-party | title=Gap years: Wasted youth? | first=Patrick | last=Kingsley | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=September 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n'''Flashpacking''' and '''Poshpacking''' refer to backpacking with more money and resources. The words combine ''backpacking'' with ''flash'', a slang term for being fancy, or ''posh'', an informal adjective for [[upper class]].<ref>{{cite news | first=Ben | last=Groundwater | title=Are you a backpacker, or a poshpacker? | url=http://blogs.smh.com.au/travel/archives/2007/01/are_you_a_backpacker_or_a_posh.html | work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | date=January 16, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title='Flashpacking?' Don't Forget you Still Need Room for Extra Socks | url=https://www.usatoday.com/travel/destinations/2006-06-19-flashpacking_x.htm | agency=[[Associated Press]] | publisher=[[USA Today]] | date=June 20, 2006}}</ref>\n\n'''Begpacking''' combines ''begging'' and ''backpacking'' in reference to individuals who [[Begging|beg]] (ask directly or indirectly for money), solicit money during [[street performance]]s, or vend (sell postcards or other small items) as a way to extend their overseas travel.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Bernstein | first=J.D. | year=2019 | title=Begging to travel: Begpacking in Southeast Asia. | journal=Annals of Tourism Research | volume=77 | pages=77, 161\u2013163 | doi=10.1016/j.annals.2018.12.014 }}</ref> The trend has drawn criticism for taking money away from people in actual need, with one known begpacker barred from entering [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Notorious begpacker barred from entering S'pore, goes around the world begging | date=April 13, 2017 | url=https://mothership.sg/2017/04/notorious-begpacker-barred-from-entering-spore/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/329837273 | title=Begging to travel: Begpacking in Southeast Asia | first=Joshua D. | last=Bernstein | date=December 2018}}</ref> Begpacking is most common in Southeast Asia and is a growing trend in South America.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/shortcuts/2019/jul/22/young-entitled-and-over-there-the-rise-of-the-begpacker | title=Young, entitled, and over there: The rise of the begpacker | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=July 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://medium.com/@MajSB/begpackers-seen-by-a-third-worldist-585d408db401 | title=Begpackers seen by a third-worldist | first=Majda | last=Saidi | work=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] | date=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary-inline|backpacking}}\n<!-- PLEASE READ: Commercial links not expanding on the article do NOT belong here.. [[Wikipedia:External links]] -->\n\n<!-- EXTERNAL LINKS SHOULD FILL THE FOLLOWING CRITERIA:\n* Be based wholly about the domain of backpacking (independent travel) and not other forms of travel,\n* Be no